definition.value: An act in which a male entertainer who dresses stereotypically, exaggeratedly, or otherwise provocatively as a woman, often accompanied by song in some form or fashion. Early female impersonators may have been recognized as transgender today. The practice also overlaps significantly with drag, specifically the conceptualization of drag queens, but these two practices are generally not considered synonymous.
A person who uses written words in various styles and techniques to communicate their ideas.
An author of novels.
One whose occupation is journalism, originally only writing in the printed press.
Journalists who write for newspapers.
Columnists who write for newspapers.
A scientist who studies genes.
A person who abstains from marriage and/or sexual relations (depending on the context).
A member of a mostly online subculture of people (typically misogynistic straight men) who define themselves by being unable to find a sexual relationship despite desiring one.

A person who experiences sexual frustration and who may label themself as an "incel" (short for involuntary celibate). Broadly, any person who wants to be sexually active, but is held back by social rules and laws.
A person who is voluntarily unmarried, sexually abstinent, or both, usually for religious reasons.
A surgeon who is concerned with conditions involving the musculoskeletal system, i.e. orthopedics.
One who studies, teaches, writes on, or does research on anatomy and anatomical structures.
A person who has some form of religious beliefs or religiosity.
A person or persons acknowledged as a leader of or within a particular religion.
A person of a religious faith who is ordained, licensed, or set apart in some way for the work of clergy within an organization or organizations.
A religious member of the clergy who is trained to perform services or sacrifices at a church or temple.
A person distinguished for their educational work, a teacher.
A person engaged in an activity related to creating art, practicing the arts, or demonstrating an art.
In common usage, "artist" usually refers to a practitioner of the visual arts only.
Journalists organized by their primary medium of authorship.
A regular writer of a column in any medium.
Columnists organized by the primary subject they write about.
Columnists organized by their primary medium of authorship.
A writer of a regular column  about sexual intercourse or other sexual activities.
Educators organized by the subject they educate persons about.
A person who is known for lecturing about, writing about, or otherwise contributing to sex education.
A person who practices one or more of the performing arts.
A person who practices one or more of the visual arts.
A person who portrays a character in a performance.
A composer, conductor, or performer of music; specifically, a person who sings and/or plays a musical instrument as a hobby, an occupation, or a profession.
A person who secretly watches and examines the actions of other individuals or organizations and gathers information on them (usually to gain an advantage).
Persons who have served in the armed forces in some capacity; members of a state's armed forces.
A person who has served and is no longer serving in armed forces.
A person who fights as part of an army. A soldier can be a conscripted or volunteer enlisted person, a non-commissioned officer, or an officer.
A person (often a woman) of social prominence, considered to be an influential figure.
The term "socialite" should only be applied in historical contexts, as its application to well-known and often powerful women could be considered sexist in many applications.
A person who supplies sex work (some form of sexual services) in exchange for compensation.

This term is promoted along with the idea that what has previously been termed prostitution should be recognized as work on equal terms with that of conventional jobs, with the legal implications this has. It is sometimes regarded as a less offensive alternative to prostitute, although "sex worker" has a much broader meaning.
A sex worker who has a male gender identity; a man who is engaged in sex work.
A sex worker who has a female gender identity; a woman who is engaged in sex work.
Sex workers who are LGBTQIA+.
Persons who are LGBTQIA+.
A person who has acquired the knowledge of computer science, the study of the theoretical foundations of information and computation and their application.
People organized by the social class they belong to, or are most associated with.
A person who belongs to a given society's upper class.
One of the aristocracy, nobility, or people of rank in a community; one of a ruling class.
A person belonging to royalty.
LGBTQIA+ persons belonging to royalty.
An agent for sex workers who collects part of their earnings.
Colloquially called a pimp (if male) or a madam (if female).
One engaged in politics, especially an elected or appointed government official.
Politicians who have any of various LGBTQIA+ identities.
Male politicians who are gay.
Female politicians who are gay.
